WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:10.640
I'm Amelia McNamara. I teach at the University of St. Thomas in Minnesota, and I tweet at

00:00:10.640 --> 00:00:17.320
AmeliaMN. I just tweeted a link to these slides in case you want to follow along.

00:00:17.320 --> 00:00:23.020
So I'm really interested in R syntax and also teaching statistics. If you are someone who

00:00:23.020 --> 00:00:28.639
teaches statistics, you know that we are always trying to have students working with multivariate

00:00:28.639 --> 00:00:33.520
data. So in this example, looking at the relationship between flipper length and bill

00:00:33.520 --> 00:00:39.520
length of penguins between different species to see if that relationship is the same.

00:00:39.520 --> 00:00:43.680
And I chose this sort of contrived example to show you why educators believe that we

00:00:43.680 --> 00:00:49.320
should not be teaching base R syntax. And that is because it can get really complicated,

00:00:49.320 --> 00:00:53.000
really verbose. It's easy to make mistakes. And if you look at those graphics, they don't

00:00:53.000 --> 00:00:58.599
even have the same consistent axes. So most educators agree we should either use the formula

00:00:59.560 --> 00:01:05.320
mosaic package or the tidyverse syntax. And both of those are going to create beautiful

00:01:05.320 --> 00:01:11.519
ggplot2 graphics with those consistent axes. But we have lots of opinions about which of

00:01:11.519 --> 00:01:19.000
these we should use and not a lot of data. So I did a semester-long head-to-head comparison

00:01:19.000 --> 00:01:25.080
of the formula and tidyverse syntaxes. Why did I do this to myself? I basically doubled

00:01:25.080 --> 00:01:30.000
my work, right? I had to create the materials in both syntaxes. I tried to make them as

00:01:30.000 --> 00:01:34.360
consistent as possible in R markdown documents that had the same text. The only thing that

00:01:34.360 --> 00:01:39.680
was different was the R syntax. And the reason for this is because I wanted to get us some

00:01:39.680 --> 00:01:45.639
data and I also really believe that constraints breed creativity. So if you put those constraints

00:01:45.639 --> 00:01:51.360
on yourself, it's going to make you more creative. So here are my results. Some things are really

00:01:51.360 --> 00:01:57.320
easy regardless of syntax. R markdown or Cordo works so well. Inference works well

00:01:57.320 --> 00:02:01.320
in intro staff, whether you're using the mosaic package for inference or the infer package

00:02:01.320 --> 00:02:06.440
in the tidyverse. But different things can be hard. So in the formula syntax, dealing

00:02:06.440 --> 00:02:11.320
with and explaining how we deal with missing data, that's pretty challenging. There's options,

00:02:11.320 --> 00:02:17.080
there's na.rm equals true, there's use equal complete ofs. That was tough. In the tidyverse,

00:02:17.080 --> 00:02:21.479
dealing with and explaining the relationship between two categorical variables was a challenge.

00:02:21.479 --> 00:02:26.119
So we're used to seeing two categorical variables explained in a two-way table. That's not a

00:02:26.119 --> 00:02:31.119
tidy data structure. And it's harder for me and for students to conceptualize of the relationship

00:02:31.119 --> 00:02:34.839
when it's in that tidy format. And that can have implications when you do things like

00:02:34.839 --> 00:02:40.520
chi-square tests and proportion tests. The other thing that I was really interested

00:02:40.520 --> 00:02:45.039
in is how much R code you really needed in an intro stat course. And it turns out not

00:02:45.039 --> 00:02:50.600
that much. So in the formula section, I exposed students to 37 functions. In the tidyverse

00:02:50.600 --> 00:02:55.100
section, they saw 50 functions. Those are a little bit different in terms of numbers.

00:02:55.100 --> 00:02:59.559
But both of them over the course of 15 weeks, totally reasonable. A big criticism of the

00:02:59.559 --> 00:03:03.440
tidyverse in teaching is, oh, there's so many tidyverse functions. How would students ever

00:03:03.440 --> 00:03:06.919
learn them all? Well, they're not going to learn them. You're just going to show them

00:03:06.919 --> 00:03:10.800
the 50 that they need. And if you look at the top five in each of these sections, I

00:03:10.800 --> 00:03:15.179
think you'll kind of see some of the differences here as well. So in the tidyverse section,

00:03:15.179 --> 00:03:19.960
I used the summarize function a lot. Every time we did summary statistics. I used the

00:03:19.960 --> 00:03:24.399
ggplot function a lot. Every time I built a graphic. Versus in the formula section,

00:03:24.399 --> 00:03:31.039
in the top five, I have the gfhistogram. And I have the mean function. So a specific summary

00:03:31.039 --> 00:03:34.880
statistic. And you'd see some of those things kind of coming up in the tidyverse section

00:03:34.880 --> 00:03:39.960
if I went further down the list. The other thing I found is there was a difference

00:03:40.000 --> 00:03:44.440
in the amount of time students were spending computing on RStudio Cloud. Students in the

00:03:44.440 --> 00:03:49.240
tidyverse section, it looks like they spent more time computing. Why is this? I have no

00:03:49.240 --> 00:03:53.759
idea. I probably should have collected some data, done some interviews, asked them, is

00:03:53.759 --> 00:03:56.720
it because you're on there? You're like, oh, it's so fun. I want to keep looking. I want

00:03:56.720 --> 00:04:00.039
to play around. Or is it because it's really tough and you're banging your head against

00:04:00.039 --> 00:04:06.919
the wall and you're frustrated? I don't know. And that's a great avenue for future investigations.

00:04:06.919 --> 00:04:10.880
If you want to try something like this yourself, if you want to know how many R functions do

00:04:10.880 --> 00:04:17.320
I show my students, use the R function get parse data. And if you want to know how much

00:04:17.320 --> 00:04:22.559
time each individual student is spending on RStudio Cloud, you can dig into your browser's

00:04:22.559 --> 00:04:27.920
developer tools to kind of sneak that data out. If you want to know more about how I

00:04:27.920 --> 00:04:33.839
did this and what I found out, I've got a preprint on the archive. And if you want my

00:04:33.839 --> 00:04:38.880
materials, my R Markdown documents, you want to see how I got that data for all my functions

00:04:38.880 --> 00:04:43.160
and how I analyzed the data for my paper, if you want to read the paper, all of that

00:04:43.160 --> 00:04:46.559
is available. I'm happy to take questions on Discord. And thanks so much.

